The notation `=ᵐ[μD]` means "equal almost everywhere" with respect to the measure `μD`, which is defined as a Dirac measure at π.

For two sets to be equal almost everywhere, their symmetric difference must have measure zero. Since `μD` is a Dirac measure at π, any set that doesn't contain π has measure zero.

